Ingestion Errors and Refresh Failures

Keep these considerations in mind when creating a Salesforce CRM data stream.

The Salesforce CRM Connector doesn’t support ingestion of Big Objects from Salesforce CRM.
The Salesforce CRM connector streaming process doesn't support data encryption with Bring Your Own Key (BYOK).
Salesforce archives Tasks and Events that are over a year old. When ingesting data, these archived records aren’t included.
Salesforce CRM data streams can fail due to missing field and object permissions. To download errors, go to the Refresh History tab of a data stream, click the error, and download the error message file.
The number of fields and values can have an impact on refresh time and could result in timeouts.
Enable Read permissions on related objects even if you don’t ingest the related objects into Data Cloud. Ingested objects that reference related objects need permissions to access the related object information and create a data stream.
To delete a field from your connected CRM, first disable that field from Data Cloud to avoid ingestion errors in data streams. See Considerations for Data Stream Field Disablement.
You can delete the DMO only if it’s a custom object.  See Delete a Data Model Object and Remove Field Mappings
The data stream Refresh History tab summarizes each data stream’s last 50 refresh operations including errors that occurred. Use the Refresh History tab to troubleshoot errors.

Here are some scenarios where Salesforce CRM data stream refreshes can fail and how you can recover from the errors.

If you don’t enable object and field permissions during Data Cloud setup, a data stream refresh can fail. Enable object and field permissions to access Salesforce CRM.
If you delete a custom field and then add it back, a scheduled or manual data stream refresh can fail to update records or status. When you add back a field, you must reenable Read Access for the field.
If you exceed the DLO to DMO mapping limit, a data stream refresh can fail to complete. Review the DMO relationship limits.
When an incremental update or full refresh is running, adding a formula field to trigger a full refresh cancels the initial update and shows as failed in the application.
How a Data Refresh Works

There are 2 phases when performing a data refresh (or data sync):

A Full Refresh: The entirety of the source data replaces the entirety of the destination data.
Incremental Refresh: Updates are made between full refreshes. Each incremental update extracts data between the start time of the prior extraction until the current time.

Data refresh in all cases has two parts:

Extraction of data from the source org.
Ingestion of data to the Data Cloud target org.

Extraction must succeed before ingestion begins. The data stream history panel shows when there are extraction and ingestion errors, or when there’s a successful ingestion. Ingestion is successful when the data is successfully written to the data lake object (DLO). The history panel doesn’t show when there’s a successful extraction, as the success message is handled by the subsequent ingestion flow.

NOTE In rare cases, if a data stream fails on extraction, the user may assume the data stream is in a bad state. For example, if connectivity between the source and target orgs was interrupted, the refresh could surface the interruption as an error. If the issue was transient and there was no new data, no message is sent for the successful extraction of no data.
